{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958062701/0316.xml":{"full_text":"THE UNION JOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, Jone 27,1958\n\u2018I Need Him\u2019\nP\nRESIDENTIAL ASSISTANT Sherman\nAdams has become a member in good\nstanding in the most exclusive political\nclub in the world, the \u201cClean as a Hound\u2019s\nTooth\u201d club organized by Pres. Eisenhow\ner for associates whose improprieties he\nhas personally condoned.\nUntil Adams\u2019 election to membership\nvia a presidential press conference state\nment, Vice Pres. Nixon was the sole mem\nber. He gained admittance in 1952 when\nthe President \u201cabsolved\u201d him of any\nwrongdoing in taking funds from Cali\nfornia businessmen for his congressional\nexpenses.\nAdams won membership on his own\nconfession of \u201cimprudence.\u201d The Presi\ndent agreed he was \u201cimprudent\u201d in ac\ncepting gifts f r o m a businessman who\nfaced potential action by a government\nregulatory agency.\nBut perhaps more meaningful than\nAdams\u2019 new membership in the club is\nMr. Eisenhower\u2019s statement that even\nthough Adams may not have exercised\ngood judgment in accepting the gifts, \"I\nneed him.\u201d\nThe President may not be in a posi\ntion to operate without his \u201cchief of staff\u201d\nbut the nation can easily do without the\nself-righteous, sanctimonious Sherman\nAdams who has established at the White\nHouse a set of moral and ethical standards\nthat reflect the worst practices of the big\nbusmess \u201cinfluence peddling\u201d philosophy.\nWho Caused the Recession?\nWE SEE WHERE 15 of the nation\u2019s top\nbusinessmen claim that \u201cexces\nsive\u201d wage increases won by Labor Un\nions have caused the recession. The busi\nnessmen made the charge in a statement\nfiled last week with the Senate Finance\nCommittee.\nAs it turned out, the 15 picked a bad\ntime to make their charge. They picked\nthe time that Business Week magazine\nreleased the results of its annual survey\nof salaries of the nation\u2019s top business\nexecutives.\nWhile the business leaders are trying\nto pin the recession\u2019s blame on workers,\nlet\u2019s see what kind of wages they received\nlast year.\nLet\u2019s look, for example, at the 1957\npay of three of the 15 businessmen who\nclaim that workers' wages have brought\nus to the brink of depression: Harlow\nCurtice, president of General Motors; L.\nL. Colbert, president of the Chrysler\nCorp., and Ralph J. Cordiner, chairman\nof the General Electric Co.\nCurtice received a 1957 salary of\n$201,000, plus a bonus of $357,775. Cor\ndiner was paid a salary of $264,973 last\nyear, which was some $5000 higher than\nthe previous year. But look what Colbert\nreceived in 1957: Total pay of $488,900,\nwhich was a raise of $238,000 over his\n1956 pay!\nThe 15 businessmen should have said\nsomething sooner than this about how\nbadly things were going for them. It\u2019s\nprobably too late now to help them, what\nwith all this unemployment and people\nout of work with no wages to cut.\nA Most Unpopular Fella\n\"TASILY THE MOST unpopular person\nD in Ohio today is Fred J. Milligan, ex\ncutive secretary of the Ohio Information\nCommittee.\u201d\nThat's how the Akron Beacon Journal\nbegan its leading editorial of June 16. The\nreason for the selection of Milligan as \u201cthe\nmost unpopular person\u201d is an obvious one.\nnot only to the Beacon Journal, but espe\ncially to thousands of unemployed\nOhioans.\nMilligan is the one who is standing in\nthe way of a speedy ruling by the Ohio\nSupreme Court on the question of supple\nmental unemployment benefits (SUB).\nEveryone is out of step but Milligan, ac\ncording to Milligan.\nAll the principals in the two SUB cases\nbefore the Court\u2014the steel companies and\nthe state\u2014are willing to waive the rule\nunder which 40 days is allowed for filing\nbriefs and file the same briefs used in the\nlower courts. But Milligan is insisting on\nthe 40 days.\n\u201cFar from being disturbed by his cur\nrent unpopularity, the thick-skinned Mil\nligan is no doubt enjoying his role,\u201d the\nBeacon Journal sizzled. \u201cHowever it\nshould be widely known that he has over\nstepped an understanding which was\nreached when he and his organization\nwere permitted to participate in the case.\u201d\nThe understanding, as the steel com\npanies pointed out in a public statement\nlast Friday, was that those involved in the\ncases \u201cwould at no stage delay the clearly\nstated desire of the main parties to get an\nearly determination of the issues, even if\nthat meant recourse to the highest court.\u201d\nThe newspaper concluded its editorial\nby asking: \"Will he (Milligan) take the\nhonorable, common-sense course by filing\nhis brief tomorrow so that the case may be\nheard within a few days? Or will he insist\non stalling?\u201d\nMilligan\u2019s reply to criticism of his stall\ning role was that \u201cthe sole purpose\u201d of the\nOhio Information Committee is to oppose\nSUB!\nThousands of unemployed and their\nfamilies are waiting for the SUB answer.\nThey need the extra help desperately. The\ndecision can come quickly except for one\nman Milligan.\nMay he never have to look for help to\nanother man who thinks his sole job is to\ndeny help.\nPaying for the Recession\nAmerica is literally paying\nthrough the nose for the nation\u2019s\nworst recession in nearly a quarter cen\ntury.\nBefore the nation gets back to the\nhigh level of employment of 1956 and\nearly 1957 the loss to the economy will\nrange between $50 and $80 billion, ac\ncording to estimates of a congressional\ncommittee staff.\nAt the current rate of activity, with\nmost economists declaring that the down\nhill movement is not yet completed and\nthat the economy will slide along at the\nbottom for many months to come, the loss\nto the nation in goods and services could\nexceed $80 billion.\nAnd this dollars and cents loss does\nnot include the suffering and despair of\nthe unemployed, the delayed purchases of\nvitally needed goods by unemployed per\nsons who cannot afford them, the critical\nlag in long overdue government welfare\nprograms.\nThis loss need not have been if the\ngovernment had moved quickly and ef\nfectively to stem the 10-month downhill\nslide by cutting taxes for low and mod\nerate income groups, by adopting a mean\ningful emergency unemployment com\npensation aid bill instead of the hoax that\nwill yield a trickle of dollars in a few\nscattered areas.\nQuote of the Week\n\"WE HAVE HAD enough of the pious\nVV (talk) that says the sputniks were a\ngood thing because they will wake us up,\nor that the reception of the Vice President\nin South America was a good thing be\ncause it showed up the weaknesses in the\nGood Neighbor policy. This is worse than\nmaking a virtue of necessity. It is making\na virtue of disaster.\u201d (President A. Whit\nney Griswold of Yale University in talk\nto Yale graduating class).\nTime Marches On\n\"FHERE ARE grounds for expecting\nthat the decline in business activity\nneed not be long.\u201d (President Eisenhower\nin his Economic Report to Congress, Jan.\nSO)\n\u201cEvery indication is that March\nshould mark the beginning of the end of\nthe downturn.\" (President Eisenhower in\na statement, February 12)\n\u201cI think there are many factors that\nwould imply that the bottom is certainly\nclose, or possibly even now reached.\u201d\n(President Eisenhower, March 26)\n\u201cI say that we are weathering it (the\nrecession) well, and I believe of course\nthat the prior boom had a great deal\nto do with the recession. Now I think it\nhas largely spent its force.\" (President\nEisenhower, May 28)\nWE SEE where Senator John Bricker\nis a member of the Senate Committee on\nOuter Space Still don\u2019t like our world,\neh John?\nLetter to the Editor\nAUTO DEALERS urge: \u2018You Auto Buy\nNow.\u2019 Mindful of price increases de\nspite the recession, I suggest a different\n(Letter\nslogan:\n\u2018You\nAuto\nCut\nNow.\u2019\n91\nfrom Milt Friedman to Washington Post,\nMay 6).\nCOMEDIAN Herb Shriner says; \u201cThe\nrecession is over; we\u2019re now in a depres\nsion.\u201d\nTOTAL EMPLOYMENT in manufac\nturing lines dropped by 271,000 to 15,095,\n000 from mid-March to mid-April, despite\nan overall rise in job totals, according to\nthe U. S. Labor and Commerce Depart\nments.\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nOfficial Publication of Organized Labor\nin Northwestern Ohio\nGrand\nAward\nWinnar\nEntered at Toledo, Ohio, Foot Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug. 36, 1111\nPublished Every Friday\nPablishing Office, 415 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nFor Information Phone CH. 1-9126\nWalter Murphy\n\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022eeoooooo\u00ab\nWilliam Borden\nDerele Collins\nEditor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nWalter Murphy, Charles Ballard,\nOtto Beebe (Local 141) .Board of Trustees\nDave Huber.Director of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCH. 4-4400 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Union Advertising, N. T.\nAl\nweexas\n\nsm/\nThink\nIt Over\nCase History Of A Gouge:\nFCC Fails Home Users\nBy AL TOFFLER\nSpecial to Union Journal\n\u25a0NIHIINHlUllUUWIMNllK'UIIMtllHIIHlWIHNtlMMU nWH\u00bbHI>IUUWWMMM\u00abHW\u00abWIMBWrri>\nWASHINGTON\u2014While a House subcom\nmittee under Arkansas\u2019 Oren Harris is reluc\ntantly exposing the fact that members of the\nFederal Communications Commission received\nfavors from the industries they are supposed to\nregulate, another House probe has come very\nclose to pinpointing what is wrong with the\nFCC\nCredit for opening the books on a reveal\ning case history goes to the House Antitrust\nSubcommittee headed by Brooklyn's Congress\nman Emanuel Celler. The story has remained\nlargely unreported, despite the fact that it in\nvolves a $159,000,000 gouge of the public.\nOn September 28, 1953 the FCC approved\na substantial hike in long distance telephone\nrates at the insistence of the American Tele\nphone and Telegraph Company. The increase\nquietly went into effect on October 1.\nSingle Dissent\nOnly one member of the Con\nsented. She was Frieda Hennock,\nn dis\nousted\nfrom the Commission by the Republican Ad\nministration. Miss Hennock charged at the\ntime that the Commission was \u201cabdicating its\nresponsibility to the public by okaying an in\ncrease without providing opponents a chance\nfor a public hearing, without taking evidence\nsubject to cross-examination, and without even\nusing some objective standard for determining\nwhat is a fair profit rate for AT&T.\u201d\nHer dissent was drowned in silence and in\nvotes favorable to AT&T.\nThe Celler Subcommittee, however, is cur\nrently analyzing the circumstances surround\ning the consent decree which AT&T got from\nan obliging Justice Deportment, insulating it\nfrom antitrust prosecution.\nIn the course of this investigation, Celler\nput a man named Bernard Strassburg on the\nwitness stand. Strassburg is FCC\u2019c top staff\nman responsible for interstate telephone rates.\nCeller found that Strassburg and the staff\nof the Commission had objected at the time\nof the rate boost. While agreeing that some\nincrease was necessary, they felt the amount to\nbe too big. Although idee of the increase was\nto permit AT&T to make 6.5 percent profit on\ninvestment for its long distance operations, no\nsooner had the increase become effective than\nthe profit rate began to soar. For 1954 it\nturned out to be 6.6 percent. In 1955 it shot\nup to 7.7 percent. In 1956 it climbed to 7.8 per\ncent. And last year it dropped only slightly to\n7.3 percent.\n$159,000,000 Gouge\nThe result has been that the public has paid\n$159,000,000 more for long distance calls than\nwould have been necessary to maintain a 6.6\nrate.\nOther public utilities, like electric compan\nies, are in contrast, regulated to permit a profit\nrate of only 4 to 6 percent.\nThus the Commission members not only\noverrode Miss Hennock's dissent, but ignored\nthe advice of their own experts. Throughout\nthe ensuing years Strassburg and the staff re\npeatedly tried to get the Commission to reduce\nlong distance telephone rates.\nOn June 13, 1955 the staff pointed out that\nthe going profit rate of \u201c7.0 to 7.5 percent\u2019*\nwas much higher than the 6.5 which \u201cit was\nestimated, would derive from the October 1,\n1953 increase.\"\nThe FCC considered the report but did\nnothing\nOn December 26, 1955 Strassburg once\nagain pointed out to the Commission members\nthat \u201cin view of the current high level of in\nterstate earnings the Commission would be\njustified in questioning the justness and rea\nsonableness of existing interstate rates.\u201d\nNo Action\nHerbert Maletz, counsel of the Celler sub\ncommittee asked Strassburg: What action did\nthe Commission take?\nReplied Strassburg: \u201cNo action...\nOn May 29, 1956, once again Strassburg\ntried. Now Bell was earning about 7 percent.\nMalets: What action was taken by the Com\nmission?\nStrassburg: None.\nStrassburg tried in July and October of\n1956. Again no action.\nFinally Strassburg in October, 1957 again\nwrote his superiors: \u201cThe diminution in the\nearnings level which was anticipated by the\nBell System has not yet made its appear\nance. The Staff view remains unchanged that\nthe current indicated return of at least 7%\npercent, using the company\u2019s reported figures\nis more than adequate to maintain the Bell\nSystem in a financially sound condition\nMaletz summed the case history up simply\nwith two more questions: At any time since\nthis rate increase was granted, did the\nCommission undertake to institute a formal\nrate investigation to determine whether the\nBell System rates were unreasonably high?\nStrassburg: No.\nCountry Lawyer\nMaletz: Thus, even though the Commission\ngranted a rate increase without a hearing,\nand even though this increase resulted in the\nBell System obtaining a rate of return in ex\ncess of 612 percent, the Commission would\nnot sanction efforts to obtain a voluntary rate\nreduction or the institution of a formal rate\ninvestigation, is that right?\nAs Vandercook\nS Sees It...\nA\nHERE HAVE lately been a few signs\nand portent that the recession may be\nslowing down. For seven weeks, the rate\nof steel production has risen. It\u2019s true,\nit has risen from a disastrously low point\nof less than half of our national steel\nmaking oapacity to a level which, in most\nother postwar years, would still be re\ngarded aS very low indeed.\nBut that is a creep, at least, in the\nright direction. Some unemployed steel\nworkers have got their jobs back again.\nGovernment bureaus have also taken\npleasure in announcing that, in the month\nof May, there was a perceptible pick-up\nin that portion of the overall American\nincome which derives from wages and\nsalaries. There are reports that the dark\ngray unemployment picture is brighten\ning.\nUnemployment, the figures say, is\ngrowing less. But do those figures take\naccount of the hundreds of thousands of\nwage-earners who simply have exhausted\ntheir unemployment benefits and, there\nfore, having been dropped from the list\nof those who get jobless benefit checks,\nare counted as no longer unemployed?\nUsually they do not.\nNor do any recent statistics take ac\ncount of the six or seven hundred thou\nsand high school and college graduates\nwho, right now, are looking for jobs.\nThe numerous welfare schemes writ\nten into law during the New and Fair\nDeal eras have helped enormously. Hun\ndreds of thousands of families have been\nsaved, thus far at any rate, from outright\ndestitution.\nBut even the wisest social legislative\nacts carry a certain peril. The danger\nthat if in this vast, resourceful, pliable\nland of ours a new class of unemployed\nsomehow manages to \u201cget by\u201d\u2014 it may\nbe forgotten. That can happen, if the\neconomic situation improves. If, say, a\nmillion American workers manage to get\njobs again, it might be all too easy to fail\nto ask what kind of jobs are they getting?\nWhat are they paid?\nAs for the rest, say three or four mil\nlion jobless, it\u2019s not hard to imagine\u2014\nif we are watchful that a time might\ncome when we would shrug our collective\nshoulders and convince ourselves that\nthat was some sort of irreducible mini\nmum; so, we could stop worrying.\nNothing, of course, could be more dis\nastrous. This is a nation dedicated to full\nemployment, to nothing less than that.\n4\nYour Union\nAnd\nMine\nBy RICHARD T. GOSSER\nVice President, UAW\nIFTEEN TOP business executives testified before the\nSenate Finance Committee on the recession. To a\nman they said the excessive wage increases obtained by\nunions had caused the recession because these increases\nhad \u201cforced\u201d them to raise their prices.\nAs long as these fellows were discussing \u201cexcessive\u201d wages\nthey should have mentioned their own salaries and bonuses and\nthe stockholders dividends.\nOne of these experts was L. L. Colbert, president of Chrys\nler and he should know about \u201cexcessive wages\u201d\u2014 last year his\npay amounted to $488,900, more than double what he made in\n1956.\nAnother one was Harlow Curtice, president of GM. His\nsalary for both 1956 and 1957 was only $201,000 but with his\nbonus each year he did very well. Last year his bonus came to\n$357,000.\nSo it would seem that both these gentlemen know about ex\ncessive wages.\nBut whether they can in all decency put that tag on the\nwages of the worker in a factory is another story. Mr. Curtice\nshould look at the wage figures of the GM worker. In 1937 the\ntake home pay of the average worker who was married and had\ntwo kids was $35.12 a week. By 1956 it was $76.50 a week, but\nwith inflated prices it amounted to only $44.41 in 1937 dollars.\nIn the eleven years between 1947 and 1958, the average\nGM worker earned a total of about $46,000 if he worked 40\nhours a week for 50 weeks each year. For the same eleven\nyears, Harlow Curtice got $1,831,000 in salary plus $4,350,000\nin bonuses for a really grand total of $6,181,000. Or to look\nat this figure another way, Mr. Curtice in eleven years made as\nmuch as 135 average GM workers did in the same time.\nf\nWE DON\u2019T EAT there should be a maximum put on what a\nman could earn a year with his talents, but we do think there\u2019s\nsomething wrong when a man who earns more than half a mil\nlion dollars a year says the guy with three dependents who\nmakes about $80 a week is getting excessive wages and shouldn\u2019t\nget more.\nIf Mr. Curtice wants to point a finger and he doesn\u2019t want\nto include the officers and directors of his company and their\nbonus plans, why does he skip the stockholder as he tries to fix\nthe blame?\nThe GM stockholder is worth a good look, even a second\nlook. Some of these stockholders managed to buy stock during\nthe depression when the market was down low. In 1932 you\ncould pick up GM stock for as low as $7.60 a share. A guy who\nhad a little money then could buy 100 shares of stock for $760.\nGM dividends weren\u2019t too good then, but GM hasn\u2019t missed\npaying dividends since 1915. And if this fellow held on to his\nhundred shares, in 1950 he got a reward. Because that year GM\ndeclared a 2 for 1 stock split and without spending another\ncent, the 100 shares became 200 shares Then in 1955, GM de\nclared another stock split, this time 3 for 1 and the 200 shares\nnow became 600 shares. And today each one of \u201cthese 600 shares\nthat cost $7.60 are worth $39 apiece, for a total value of $23,400.\nFrom a dividend in 1932 of 21 cents per share, our stock\nholder\u2019s dividends have risen as high as $2.17 a share. In 1950,\nwhen the first stock split took place, the dividends were $2.00\na share, so he got $400 just in dividends. By the time his stock\nhad multiplied to 600 shares and the dividend rate was $2.17,\nhis dividends amounted to $1,302. In fact since 1947, the guy\nwith 100 shares has not only increased his holdings to 600\nshares, but has collected about $5,400 just in dividends.\nIf our hero had enough money in 1932 to buy 1,000 shares,\nyou can imagine the profit on his return\u20146,000 shares today\nworth $234,000 and $54,000 in dividends in eleven years. You\ncould almost say this was an \u201cexcessive\u201d return.\nY\nr\nOBVIOUSLY TO PAY aU these dividends on shares that\nhave multiplied six times and to pay bonuses to its executives,\nGM has had to have profits and very high ones. Because in addi\ntion to dividends and bonuses, GM has had a great plant expan\nsion in recent years, and they claim their need for high profits\nfor this cost.\nWell, let's look a little closer at this plant expansion pro\ngram. It used to be that a company that wanted to expand would\n.put a new stock or bond issue on the market. Nowdays it pays\nfor its new plant investment through increased prices to the\nconsumers and keeps its profits for bonuses or stock dividends,\nand blames the increase in price on labor. In fact in 1950, when\nGM declared its first stock split of 2 for 1, the corporation\u2019s net\nincome was actually more than enough to repay its entire net\nplant investment in that one year.\nFor such a quick return on investment for a corporation,\nthis needs not \"excessive\" profits, but fabulous profits.\nSo it seems that if Mr. Curtice wanted to discuss an \"ex\ncessive\" item in GM's operations, he had a wider choice than\njust the poor worker\u2019s wages. And it\u2019s even more peculiar that\nhe blames these wages for the lack of purchasing power.\nBecause this recession won\u2019t end with buy campaigns and\nwith slogans\u2014it will end when people have more money to buy\nthings with. Taking the swollen profits of past years and giving\nthem to a number of stockholders and executives won't do the\ntrick. Part of those profits have to be given to the worker in\nthe factory in the form of wages so he can buy the products he\nmaker.\nIt's too bad the only investments GM rewards are the dol\nlars invested in stocks and bonds and the talents of executives\nwho drive for higher and higher profits without regard for the\npublic welfare.\nAnd that's where the union comes in because we feel the\nworker has invested years of his working life to produce these\nfantastic profits and has a moral right to share in them. Let the\nexecutive. collect his big bonus and let the stockholder rake in\nhigh dividends and then let\u2019s go further and let the worker\nmake enough money to provide a decent life for his wife and\nkids. But let\u2019s not say the first two things are right and the\nthird one will ruin the country, because that third group is the\ncountry.\nt\n\nBulletin Board\nMeetings scheduled for week of June 28th thru July 4th\nSaturday, June 28\nACKLIN 10:00 A.M. Parlor H\nSunday, June 29\nCHAMPION 2:00 P.M. Parlor A\nMonday, June 39\nNONE SCHEDULED\nTuesday, July 1\nTILLOTSON 8.00 P.M. Parlor A\nENSIGN 8.00 P.M. Parlor B\nSTD. EQUIPMENT 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nPIPE THREADING OFFICE 7:30 P.M. Parlor H\nWednesday, July 2\nDEVILBISS 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nINTERNATIONAL HARVESTER\n5:30 P.M. Parlor B\nTILLOTSON 1:00 P.M. Parlor B\nT. U. J. CIRCULATION 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nALLIED WHEEL 4:15 P.M. Parlor H\nThursday, July 3\nDEVILBISS 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nCHAMPION 11:30 A.M. Parlor A\nCHAMPION 7:30 P.M. Parlor A\nFORT PITT 8:00 P.M. Room 309\nFriday, July 4\nHOLIDAY","height":"26788","width":"19512"}}
